## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why This Breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcibly injecting exceptions into threads. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

---

### Patterns Identified

| Pattern | Old API | Replacement |
|---------|---------|-------------|
| Cancellable work loop | `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` |
| Cleanup on abort | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| Continue after abort | `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `IsCancellationRequested`, continue loop |
| Force-stop blocked call | `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` passed to blocking call |

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed; loop condition handles continuation vs exit.
                // If you wanted to continue processing (like ResetAbort did),
                // you'd use a per-item CancellationTokenSource instead.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        if (!_workerThread.Join(timeout.Value))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. Log a warning — you cannot force-kill it.
            // In .NET 8, if the code truly can't cooperate, move it to a child process.
            Console.WriteLine("Warning: worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

### Key Changes to Blocking Methods

Your `GetNextItem()` likely blocks. You **must** make it cancellation-aware:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt it
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER: accepts token, throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // wakes immediately when token fires
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep` or `WaitHandle.WaitOne`:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep(ms) with:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms); // returns early if cancelled

// Replace manualResetEvent.WaitOne() with:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { manualResetEvent, token.WaitHandle });
```

---

### If You Need Per-Item Cancellation (ResetAbort Equivalent)

The original code used `ResetAbort` to let the loop continue after aborting one item. To replicate this — cancel one item but keep processing:

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken shutdownToken)
{
    while (!shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Per-item timeout: cancel one item without stopping the loop
        using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(shutdownToken);
        itemCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)); // per-item timeout

        try
        {
            var item = GetNextItem(shutdownToken);
            ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Item timed out, but shutdown wasn't requested — continue loop
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why It Matters |
|---------|----------------|
| **Not passing token to blocking calls** | `CancellationToken` can't interrupt `Thread.Sleep` or `socket.Receive`. You must use cancellation-aware alternatives. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers/callbacks. Always `using` or `Dispose()`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated exceptions. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside long `ProcessItem` work. |
| **Relying on `Thread.Join` without timeout after cancel** | If the thread ignores cancellation, `Join()` blocks forever. Always pass a timeout. |

---

### Verification Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `ResetAbort` references
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` disposed via `IDisposable`
- ✅ Blocking calls accept `CancellationToken`
- ✅ `Stop()` uses `Join(timeout)` instead of `Thread.Abort`
- ✅ Builds cleanly on `net8.0` with no `SYSLIB0006` warnings
